---
description: Explicit, beginner-friendly code style. No clever shortening.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Readable Code Style

Optimize for someone reading the code top-to-bottom for the first time.
"Clever" or "concise" is not a win here. Each line should do one thing.

These rules apply to ALL languages in this repo (TypeScript, JavaScript, SQL,
PowerShell, Python). Examples below use TS but the spirit is universal.

## 1. Always use braces on conditionals - even one-liners

```ts
// BAD - no braces, easy to misread when scanning
if (user === null) return;
if (!ok) throw new Error('boom');

// GOOD - braces always, even for a single statement
if (user === null) {
  return;
}

if (!ok) {
  throw new Error('boom');
}
```

Same for `else`, `for`, `while`. Never inline the body.

## 2. No ternary operator (`a ? b : c`)

Use a real `if / else` with braces.

```ts
// BAD
const label = count === 0 ? 'empty' : 'has items';
return s === '' ? null : s;

// GOOD
let label;
if (count === 0) {
  label = 'empty';
} else {
  label = 'has items';
}

if (s === '') {
  return null;
}
return s;
```

## 3. No method chains - one operation per line

If you find yourself writing `foo().bar().baz()`, split it. Each step gets
its own line and its own named variable. Read top-to-bottom, inner step first.

```ts
// BAD - two operations on one line, reads outside-in
const cleaned = String(input).trim();
const ids = rows.filter(r => r.active).map(r => r.id);

// GOOD - one operation per line, reads top-to-bottom
const asString = String(input);
const cleaned  = asString.trim();

const activeRows = rows.filter(function (r) { return r.active; });
const ids = activeRows.map(function (r) { return r.id; });
```

Exception: a single `.then()` after `await`-able promise chains is fine, and
fluent SQL builders are fine. The rule targets data-transform chains.

## 4. No arrow-function bodies without an explicit `return`

```ts
// BAD - implicit return, easy to miss
const ids = rows.map(r => r.id);
const ok = list.find(x => x.id === target);

// GOOD - body, braces, explicit return
const ids = rows.map(function (r) {
  return r.id;
});

const ok = list.find(function (x) {
  return x.id === target;
});
```

Plain arrow functions are still OK for short callbacks where the body is
literally `return X` and there's no `.then()` chain - e.g.
`setTimeout(() => doThing(), 100)`. The rule targets data transforms.

## 5. Name every intermediate value

If a value is used later or makes a step easier to read, give it a name.

```ts
// BAD - magic literal inside a call
res.status(201).json({ id });

// GOOD
const CREATED = 201;
res.status(CREATED).json({ id });
```

Don't go overboard - don't name single-use constants that are already clear
in context (e.g. `res.json([])`). Use judgment: would a beginner pause and
ask "what does that mean"?

## 6. No optional-chaining + nullish-coalescing combos on one line

```ts
// BAD
const userId = (req as any)?.user?.id ?? null;

// GOOD
const reqAny = req as any;
let userId = null;
if (reqAny !== null && reqAny !== undefined) {
  if (reqAny.user !== null && reqAny.user !== undefined) {
    userId = reqAny.user.id;
  }
}
```

If a single `?.` makes a line clearer (e.g. `rows[0]?.value`), keep it. The
rule targets stacked `?.` + `??` chains that hide three checks in one line.

## 7. Always declare return types and parameter types in TS

```ts
// BAD - inferred
function nullable(v) {
  ...
}

// GOOD - explicit
function nullable(v: unknown): string | null {
  ...
}
```

## 8. Express route registration shape

Every route registration in `src/routes/*.ts` must use one of the two shapes
below. Pick the variant based on how many middlewares you have.

### Variant A - single header line (0 or 1 middlewares)

```
router.<method>(<path>, <middleware?>, async (req: Request, res: Response) =>
  {
    // handler body
  }
);
```

- The path, the (optional) single middleware, and the arrow signature go on **one header line**.
- The arrow body's opening `{` goes on its **own line**, indented under the header.
- Closing `}` lines up with the opening `{`.
- Closing `);` of the `router.<method>(...)` call sits on its **own final line**, at the original indentation.
- One blank line between routes.

Examples:

```ts
// no middleware
accountsRouter.get('/accounts/valuation-deals', async (_req: Request, res: Response) =>
  {
    const rows = await callFn(FN_VALUATION_DEALS);
    res.json(rows);
  }
);

// one middleware
accountsRouter.get('/accounts/summary', requirePermission('Accounts', 'read:summary'), async (req: Request, res: Response) =>
  {
    // handler
  }
);
```

### Variant B - multi-line (2 or more middlewares)

When you have 2+ middlewares, switch to one-argument-per-line. The header line
shape from Variant A becomes unreadable past 1 middleware.

```
router.<method>(
  <path>,
  <middleware1>,
  <middleware2>,
  ...
  async (req: Request, res: Response) =>
    {
      // handler body
    }
);
```

Notes for Variant B:
- The opening `(` is at the **end of the first line** (the `router.<method>(` line).
- Each argument is on its own line, indented one level, comma at the end (no trailing comma after the last arg).
- The arrow signature `async (req, res) =>` is the **last argument** and is on its own line.
- The arrow's opening `{` is on its own line, indented **one extra level** below the arrow.
- The handler body lives one level deeper still.
- Closing `}` lines up with the opening `{`.
- Closing `);` lines up with the original `router.<method>(...`.

Example:

```ts
accountsRouter.post(
  '/accounts/transaction',
  authMiddleware,
  requirePermission('Accounts', 'create'),
  rateLimit({ max: 5, perMinute: 1 }),
  async (req: Request, res: Response) =>
    {
      // handler
    }
);
```

### Switch rule

| # of middlewares | Shape       |
| ---------------- | ----------- |
| 0                | Variant A   |
| 1                | Variant A   |
| 2 or more        | Variant B   |

Never mix the two in one file unless the route counts genuinely require it.

### Why this shape

- The header line of Variant A tells the whole story at a glance: HTTP method, path, who can call it, that it's `async`. A reader can scan a file and see the routing surface without parsing multi-line headers.
- Variant B keeps that scannability when you genuinely need more middlewares - each is on its own line, lined up, easy to count, easy to comment / disable.
- The opening `{` on its own line makes the handler body visually a block, not a continuation of an expression.
- The trailing `);` on its own line is a hard right-margin so it's obvious where the registration ends.

This is non-idiomatic JavaScript (most formatters put the `{` on the previous line). Don't let a Prettier / ESLint config override it - we accept the deviation in exchange for the readability we want.

## 9. File ordering: imports, then ALL consts, then helpers, then routes

Every source file should read top-to-bottom in this fixed order. A reader
scrolling the file should never have to scroll past functions and then
hit another block of constants further down.

```
1.  imports
2.  exported router / singleton (one line)
3.  ALL module-level `const` declarations (grouped, with section comments)
4.  helper functions (top-level, used by the routes)
5.  route registrations
```

### BAD - a const buried between helpers

```ts
import { Router } from 'express';

export const r = Router();

const FN_GET = 'api.thing_get';

function readUserId(req) {
  // ...
}

// Buried! Reader scrolls past helpers and trips over this.
const CLOSURE_STATUSES = ['completed', 'closed'];

function isClosureStatus(value) {
  return CLOSURE_STATUSES.includes(value);
}

r.get('/thing', ...);
```

### GOOD - every const is in the top block

```ts
import { Router } from 'express';

export const r = Router();

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Function names.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
const FN_GET = 'api.thing_get';

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Domain enums.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
const CLOSURE_STATUSES = ['completed', 'closed'];

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Helpers.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

function readUserId(req) {
  // ...
}

function isClosureStatus(value) {
  return CLOSURE_STATUSES.includes(value);
}

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Routes.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

r.get('/thing', ...);
```

### Why

- A reader who only wants to know "what tables / functions / error codes does this file touch" can read the top of the file and stop.
- Helpers and routes never need to forward-reference; if they need a name, it's already declared above. No mental hoisting required.
- Section comments (the dashed banners) act as a table of contents.

Group related consts together and add a single-line section comment per group
(e.g. `// HTTP status codes.`, `// PG error codes.`, `// Function names.`).
Never declare a stray `const` between two helpers or between two routes - if
it feels too specific to live at the top, it probably belongs inline inside
the one route that uses it, not as a module-level constant.

## Canonical rewrite of `nullable`

The shape every helper in this repo should follow:

```ts
function nullable(v: unknown): string | null {
  if (v === undefined) {
    return null;
  }
  if (v === null) {
    return null;
  }

  const asString = String(v);
  const trimmed = asString.trim();

  if (trimmed === '') {
    return null;
  }
  return trimmed;
}
```

Yes it's longer. That is the point.
